LAGOS  – Officials of the National Drug Law Enforcement Agency (NDLEA) attached to the Murtala Muhammed International Airport (MMIA), Lagos, have in­tercepted a consignment of 22 international passports of six different countries concealed in a bag of gar­ri, among other food items. NDLEA in a statement by Mr. Femi Babafemi, its spokesman, said that the items were discovered at the export shed of the Sky­ways Aviation Handling Company (SAHCO) Plc during the routine cargo search at the shed. The statement noted that nine of the passports were three each of United King­dom, France and Portugal. 2023: I’ll Rather Return Home Than Join APC – Senator… NURTW Clashes: Bode George Blames Sanwo-Olu, Says Lagos Island… Others were of Nigeria, eight; Ghana, four, and Cameroon, one interna­tional passport. Attempts to get reaction from SAHCO proved abor­tive as its spokesperson could not be reached as at the time of filing this re­port. Besides, at the airport operatives equally recov­ered 12 parcels of cannabis weighing 4.95kg concealed in a carton of Golden Morn packaged for export through the same SAHCO export shed. In a related develop­ment, three trans-border drug traffickers have been arrested by operatives of the NDLEA, while trying to smuggle 48,000 tablets of 225mg Tramadol through Mubi, Adamawa State to Cameroon. The statement said: “Over 1,500 kilogrammes of imported Loud and other illicit substances have been intercepted in raids across Lagos and Edo states.’” POLL The suspects: Moham­med Hussaini, 32; Adamu Bella, 18, and Mohammed Umar, 18, were arrested at Tsamiya Junction, Madan­ya Road, Mubi, Mubi North Local Government Area (LGA), Adamawa State on Friday, January 28, with the exhibits concealed in the packets of another drug. When interrogated, the suspects claimed the drugs were being taken to Bagira town along Nigeria-Camer­oon border to be delivered to some Cameroonians for onward delivery to Maroa in Cameroon.